                            <td height="25" valign="top"><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" color="#683400" style="font-size:14px;"><strong><em>Are you teaching your child the basics of  financial planning?</em></strong></font></td>
                          </tr>

                            <tr>
                              <td valign="top" style="font-family:Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; color:#333333; font-size:12px; text-align:justify;">As adults, we  know the importance that money and finances play in our lives. Yet, many of us  learn the hard way that we need to be wise with our investments and  expenditures to lead a financially stables life. With the infusion of financial  planning we are able to define our dreams into goals, and then articulate these  goals in financial terms, giving us targets that we strive to achieve.<br />
                                <br />
                                Yet, while we  ourselves try to imbibe financial planning into our lives, how many of us have  actually thought about the next generation by taking an effort to teach kids  about the value of money or the basics of financial planning.<br />
                                <br />
                                If you have a  child dependent on you, start sharing lessons on money management with the kid  from an early stage, so that by the time the child becomes an adult he/she will  not make the kind of mistakes that one normally makes in youth.<br />
                                <br />
                                To start your child on financial planning you can start off with –</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                              <td valign="top" style="font-family:Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; color:#333333; font-size:12px; text-align:justify;"><ol>
                                <li><strong>Personal finance basics for kids</strong><br />
                                  As a parent,  the worst thing one can do is assume that the child will automatically learn  personal finance. The lessons for personal finance have to begin at home since  there is no other avenue where the child can learn.<br />
                                &nbsp;</li>
                                <li><strong>Make them  feel responsible</strong><br />
                                  Most parents do  this but probably not consciously enough. Set a monthly allowance for your  child, and let him/her do chores around the house to ‘earn’ more money. When  your child comes to you for an iPad tell him that to get the iPad, he will have  to save atleast part of the money before you go ahead and buy it for him.<br />
                                &nbsp;</li>
                                <li><strong>Teach about limited resources to manage multiple needs</strong><br />
                                  Kids will come to you with multiple demands based on what they see their  friends carrying. It could be a bicycle or the newest tech-gadget. Tell the  child that you cannot buy him everything that he needs and the limit to which  you can spend on his demands every year. Then, sit with your child and ask him  to make a choice between his desires, in process rationalizing his wants.<br />
                                &nbsp;</li>
                                <li><strong>Involve them in family finances</strong><br />
                                  Children always desire to be treated like adults. Involve your child in setting  and maintaining your monthly household budget. Based on your child’s age, try  to involve the child in the family financial plan as well. Explain the  financial plan to the child starting with how goals are articulated in  financial terms. Also, try to explain to the child how you go about ensuring  that your desires do not derail your long term vision.<br />
                                &nbsp;</li>
                                <li><strong>Compounding and how it can help </strong><br />
                                  If you have set up an education fund for your child, explain to him how by  starting early you have been able to capitalize on the power of compounding. &nbsp;On  a regular basis, share the progress towards the goal with your child, giving  him an insight into how regular investments attaining a goal. <br />
                                &nbsp;</li>
                                <li><strong>The credit trap</strong><br />
                                  Most parents  today hand a credit card to children during their mid-teens. Such a step can be  extremely detrimental towards their understanding of money. If you must give  your child a credit card, ensure that you first explain to the child that money  spent on the card has to be paid at the end of each month and how the child  should be responsible before making a credit purchase. Also, try to opt for a  credit card where you can set a monthly limit on the expenditure to ensure a  maximum cap on the purchases.</li>
                              </ol></td>
                            </tr>
